due to impaired energy production. \u003Cstrong\u003ECoenzyme Q10\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzymatic cofactor that can be supplemented to treat mitochondrial myopathies. It plays a crucial role in the electron transport chain, which is essential for ATP production in mitochondria. Supplementation with Coenzyme Q10 can help improve mitochondrial function and alleviate symptoms associated with mitochondrial myopathies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E - While important for nerve function and red blood cell production, it does not directly address mitochondrial dysfunction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolic acid\u003C/strong\u003E - Primarily involved in DNA synthesis and repair, not mitochondrial function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron\u003C/strong\u003E - Essential for haemoglobin and myoglobin, but not specifically for mitochondrial myopathies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium\u003C/strong\u003E - Important for bone health and muscle contraction, but not directly related to mitochondrial function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coenzyme Q10 is an enzymatic cofactor that can be supplemented to treat mitochondrial myopathies.","Mitochondrial myopathies are a group of neuromuscular diseases caused by damage to the mitochondria.","Coenzyme Q10 plays a crucial role in the electron transport chain, which is essential for ATP production."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textb